<header class="header">
  <h1>How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    Time defines the window. Heat determines development.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    Frost dates define your growing season boundary at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
    Growing Degree Days (GDD) measure how much usable heat accumulates inside that boundary.
  </p>

  <p>
    Together, they determine whether a crop can realistically reach maturity before frost returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    Looking at either one alone is incomplete.
    Planning becomes reliable only when you model both constraints together.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Frost Boundary: Defining the Season</h2>

  <p>
    Frost dates are based on <strong>1991–2020 climate normals</strong>
    and typically expressed at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    That means:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>About half of years will experience frost earlier than the listed date.</li>
    <li>About half will experience frost later.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Two frost events define your planning window:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Last spring frost (32°F / 0°C)</strong></li>
    <li><strong>First fall frost (32°F / 0°C)</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The period between them is your frost-free window.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can identify your boundaries using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But frost-free days alone do not guarantee crop maturity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Growing Degree Days: Measuring Seasonal Heat</h2>

  <p>
    Crops do not mature because a certain number of days pass.
    They mature because they accumulate enough heat.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most warm-season crops, heat accumulation is measured using a base of
    <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Each day that exceeds the base threshold contributes heat units.
    Over time, those units accumulate into your <strong>seasonal heat budget</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate how much heat typically accumulates before first frost using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Frost-Free Days Are Not Enough</h2>

  <p>
    Consider two locations:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Both have 110 frost-free days.</li>
    <li>Both plant tomatoes immediately after last frost.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Location A accumulates 2,300 GDD before first frost.
    Location B accumulates 1,600 GDD.
  </p>

  <p>
    In Location A, most tomato varieties mature comfortably.
    In Location B, only short-season varieties succeed reliably.
  </p>

  <p>
    The calendar window is identical.
    The seasonal heat budget is not.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why days-to-maturity labels can mislead in cold climates.
    See
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>
    for deeper explanation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Interaction: Time × Heat</h2>

  <p>
    Frost defines how long crops can grow.
    GDD defines how fast they develop during that time.
  </p>

  <p>
    If the frost window is long but temperatures are cool,
    development is slow.
  </p>

  <p>
    If temperatures are warm but frost returns early,
    crops may not have enough total time to accumulate required heat.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crop success requires alignment between:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Available time before frost</li>
    <li>Available heat accumulation</li>
    <li>Crop heat requirement</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Applied Modeling Example</h2>

  <p><strong>Example Crop:</strong> Tomato requiring 1,700 GDD</p>

  <p><strong>Location A</strong><br>
  Frost-free window: 120 days<br>
  Seasonal GDD: 2,200<br>
  Outcome: Comfortable margin</p>

  <p><strong>Location B</strong><br>
  Frost-free window: 110 days<br>
  Seasonal GDD: 1,750<br>
  Outcome: Borderline margin</p>

  <p><strong>Location C</strong><br>
  Frost-free window: 105 days<br>
  Seasonal GDD: 1,400<br>
  Outcome: Heat deficit before frost</p>

  <p>
    Notice that calendar days alone cannot reveal these differences.
    Only modeling frost timing and heat accumulation together can.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Margin Near the Frost Boundary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Comfortable:</strong> Seasonal GDD exceeds crop requirement by several hundred units.</li>
    <li><strong>Borderline:</strong> Seasonal GDD closely matches requirement.</li>
    <li><strong>Unlikely:</strong> Seasonal GDD typically falls short.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Because frost dates use probability framing,
    cooler summers or earlier fall frosts reduce effective margin.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short climates, operating with margin is often more important than selecting ambitious crops.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why This Model Replaces Calendar Advice</h2>

  <p>
    Traditional planting calendars use fixed dates.
  </p>

  <p>
    Climate-based planning uses constraints:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost boundary → season length → GDD → crop requirement → risk margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    When those constraints align, maturity becomes predictable in a typical year.
    When they do not, crops cross the frost boundary before completing development.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a broader explanation of why frost boundaries outperform fixed dates, see
    <a href="/guides/why-frost-dates-matter-more-than-planting-calendars/">Why Frost Dates Matter More Than Planting Calendars</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Frost dates define your climate boundary at 32°F (0°C).</li>
    <li>They are based on 1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days measure accumulated heat above 50°F (10°C).</li>
    <li>Crop maturity depends on total heat accumulated before frost returns.</li>
    <li>Reliable planning requires modeling time and heat together.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Frost defines the window.
    Heat determines whether crops finish inside it.
  </p>
</section>